'''Tenk Lenso''' was a [[Human/Legends|Human]] [[Gender/Legends|male]] native of the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Glova]] who served with the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Alliance to Restore the Republic]] as a [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighter]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] during the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]]. His career included service with the [[Deretta Destroyers]], a mixed fighter [[Squadron/Legends|squadron]], where he proved his abilities as a [[Gunner/Legends|gunner]] in a [[BTL-S3 Y-wing starfighter/Legends|BTL-S3 Y-wing]]. After his squadron was all but [[Battle of Tarabba|destroyed]] during a raid on an [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] depot, Lenso was transferred to the Rebellion's [[Echo Base/Legends|Echo Base]] on the ice [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Hoth/Legends|Hoth]] and earned a place with the elite [[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue Group]] under the [[Callsign/Legends|call sign]] [[Rogue Eleven/Legends|Rogue Eleven]]. Lenso flew with the Rogues during the [[Battle of Hoth/Legends|Battle of Hoth]], participating in the [[Evac Rearguard Action 101|delaying action]] that helped much of the base's personnel and equipment to escape the Imperial siege, but he was among the first to be shot down during the engagement.

==Biography==
{{Quote|Just give me one clean shot.|Tenk Lenso|<ref name="GG3 1st" />}}
===Service with the Deretta Destroyers===
The [[Human/Legends|Human]] [[Gender/Legends|male]]<ref name="GG3" /> Tenk Lenso hailed from the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Glova]].<ref name="EGW" /> One of Lenso's earliest assignments with the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Alliance to Restore the Republic]] during the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]] saw him serving with the [[Deretta Destroyers]], a mixed [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighter]] [[Squadron/Legends|squadron]] consisting of [[T-65 X-wing starfighter/Legends|T-65 X-wing]] and [[BTL Y-wing starfighter/Legends|BTL Y-wing starfighters]]. The Destroyers were staged on the [[Moon/Legends|moon]] of [[Deretta]], from which they received their moniker. There, Lenso proved his skill as a [[Gunner/Legends|gunner]] aboard a [[BTL-S3 Y-wing starfighter/Legends|BTL-S3 Y-wing starfighter]].<ref name="GG3" />

Shortly before the [[Battle of Hoth/Legends|Battle of Hoth]], the Destroyers were tasked with the [[Battle of Tarabba|elimination]] of an [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] depot, a typical assignment for the group&mdash;they were in part named for their ordnance-heavy [[Proton torpedo/Legends|proton torpedo]] strikes on such targets. While the Destroyers entered the target zone ahead of their main attack force and softened up the opposition, they were prevented from leaving after their initial strike by the presence of an Imperial [[Immobilizer 418 Interdictor-class Heavy Cruiser|Immobilizer 418 cruiser]], a [[Capital ship/Legends|capital ship]] equipped with four [[Gravity well projector/Legends|gravity well projectors]] capable of restricting [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]] travel. Several excruciatingly slow [[Standard minute/Legends|minutes]] passed for the group while they waited for the main Rebel strike force to arrive, during which all twelve Destroyers were wiped out.<ref name="GG3" />

Lenso managed to eject from his fighter at the last minute as his Y-wing was shot out from under him, but not before finding himself trapped in the [[Cockpit/Legends|cockpit]]. Heavy flak and [[Laser/Legends|laser]] fire from the battle killed his [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] after the fighter's [[Deflector shield/Legends|deflector shields]] were overloaded, and Lenso had no control over the craft; his ejection mechanism locked up. With a [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE/LN starfighter]] lining up for the kill on the Y-wing, Lenso was able to climb over his [[Death/Legends|dead]] pilot and fire the ejection system. He held onto the [[Ejector seat/Legends|ejector seat]] as it jettisoned from the fighter, the blast knocking him unconscious. Although the Rebels eventually claimed victory at the depot skirmish, the loss of the Destroyers was a substantial blow.<ref name="GG3" />

===Transfer to Hoth===
{{Quote|This thing's headed straight for the base&hellip;We're gonna have to take a crack at it.''"<br />"''&hellip;I'll have Rogue Ten and Rogue Eleven make an attack run&hellip;''"<br />"''&hellip;There's no time for that. Besides, if it sees the snowspeeders, it'll know we're here for sure&hellip;|Han Solo and General Carlist Rieekan discuss Lenso possibly attacking the Viper probe droid|<ref name="ESB script">[[The Empire Strikes Back: The National Public Radio Dramatization|''The Empire Strikes Back'': The National Public Radio Dramatization]]</ref>}}
[[File:SnowspeederPatrol-SW39.png|thumb|left|297px|Tenk Lenso and Rogue Ten, Tarrin Datch, were dispatched to Echo Station 3-8 to investigate the probe droid.]]
Eventually rescued by a Rebel [[Hospital ship/Legends|medical frigate]], Lenso was soon transferred to the [[Echo Base medical center/Legends|medical lab]] at the Rebels' secret [[Echo Base/Legends|Echo Base]] on the remote ice [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Hoth/Legends|Hoth]], where he received further treatment in the facility's [[Bacta tank/Legends|bacta tank]]. At some point, he was assigned to the elite starfighter squadron [[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue Group]], as [[Rogue Eleven/Legends|Rogue Eleven]], under the command of [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]]. Due to psychological trauma sustained during the depot run,<ref name="GG3" /> including flashbacks,<ref name="EGW" /> Lenso found that he could no longer operate as a gunner. Instead, he flew an X-wing with the Rogues.<ref name="GG3" />

When an Imperial reconnaissance [[Viper probe droid/Legends|Viper probe droid]] discovered Echo Base in [[3 ABY/Legends|3 ABY]], Lenso and [[Rogue Ten/Legends|Rogue Ten]], [[Tarrin Datch/Legends|Tarrin Datch]], were among the first pilots dispatched by base commander [[General/Legends|General]] [[Carlist Rieekan/Legends|Carlist Rieekan]] to investigate the threat.<ref name="GG3" /><ref name="ESB" /><ref name="ESB novel">[[Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back (novelization)|''Star Wars Episode V: The Empire Strikes Back'' novelization]]</ref><ref name="BTM">''[[Star Wars: Behind the Magic]]''</ref> Rieekan instructed Lenso and Datch to fly a holding pattern at low altitude over [[Echo Station 3-8]] and to expect trouble.<ref name="ESB radio drama">[[The Empire Strikes Back (radio)|''The Empire Strikes Back'' radio drama]]</ref> They investigated Echo Station 3-8 and also transported [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] and the [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiee]] [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]] to the area aboard [[T-47 airspeeder/Legends|T-47 airspeeders]], dubbed "[[Snowspeeder/Legends|snowspeeders]]."<ref name="CSWE">''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]''</ref> After Solo and Chewbacca located the probe soon thereafter and informed Rieekan that it may have detected the base's [[Deflector shield generator/Legends|shield generator]], Rieekan intended to order Lenso and Datch on an attack run for the [[Droid/Legends|droid]]. Solo, however, dismissed the idea, claiming that there was no time for that, and that the sight of overhead flying snowspeeders would alert the probe to their presence. Instead, he told Rieekan that he and Chewbacca would destroy the probe themselves.<ref name="ESB script" /> Although Solo and Chewbacca did eliminate the probe, the droid had already transmitted the location of Echo Base to the Empire.<ref name="ESB" />

[[File:Rogue_Group_TESB_Manga.jpg|250px|thumb|The twelve airspeeders of Rogue Group, including pilot Lenso, attack during the Battle of Hoth.]]
The probe's discovery of the Rebel presence on the planet led to the subsequent [[Battle of Hoth/Legends|Battle of Hoth]]. During the engagement, Lenso flew with the Rogues, tasked with the duty of [[Evac Rearguard Action 101|delaying]] the advance of an invading line of Imperial [[All Terrain Armored Transport/Legends|All Terrain Armored Transport]] [[Walker/Legends|walkers]] long enough for Echo Base's [[Transport/Legends|transports]] and personnel to escape the planet. Still hampered by his mental scars, Lenso opted to sit in the "front-row seat" of one of the base's modified [[Airspeeder/Legends|snowspeeders]], rather than the familiar gunnery seat.<ref name="GG3" /> His gunner was [[Jek Pugilio]].<ref name="EGW" /> While the Rogues succeeded in buying enough time for much of Echo Base to evacuate Hoth, the Rebels nevertheless suffered heavy casualties. Lenso was killed when his speeder was one of the first shot down during the engagement.<ref name="GG3" />

==Personality and traits==
Tenk Lenso was a capable gunner, having proven his skills in the rear of a Y-wing while serving with the Deretta Destroyers. However, the heavy losses sustained during the destruction of the Destroyers on their final mission proved to be too much for the man to bear. He found he could no longer effectively serve as a gunner in [[Starfighter combat/Legends|combat]]. The stresses of battle fatigue would ultimately prove to be Lenso's undoing, as his piloting abilities, less honed by comparison, failed him during the Battle of Hoth.<ref name="GG3" />

Aside from his considerable starfighter gunnery and piloting abilities, Lenso was particularly skilled in mechanical airspeeder [[Repulsorlift/Legends|repulsorlift]] operation and repair, [[Starship/Legends|starship]] [[Astrogation/Legends|astrogation]], and was adept at beast riding. He was also knowledgeable about planetary [[Star system/Legends|star systems]].<ref name="GG3" />

==Behind the scenes==
[[File:TenkLenso_GG3.jpg|thumb|right|165px|Lenso in ''[[Galaxy Guide 3: The Empire Strikes Back]]'']]
{{Quote|Send Rogue Ten and Rogue Eleven to station three-eight and have them fly a holding pattern there at low altitude&hellip;and tell them to expect trouble.|General Carlist Rieekan's alternate lines from the script to ''The Empire Strikes Back'' radio drama|<ref name="ESB script" />}}
The character of Tenk Lenso first appeared in the [[1989]] first edition of the [[West End Games]] sourcebook ''[[Galaxy Guide 3: The Empire Strikes Back]]'' as an example of a standard [[Rebel pilot/Legends|Rebel snowspeeder pilot]], providing the character with a name and [[Roleplaying game|roleplaying]] stats only.<ref name="GG3 1st" /> The black and white artwork accompanying the article (seen here) was previously used in ''[[Galaxy Guide 1: A New Hope]]'' alongside the name and stats of pilot [[Fin Danglot]]. The [[1996]] [[Galaxy Guide 3: The Empire Strikes Back (Second Edition)|second edition]] of ''Galaxy Guide 3'' included a full profile for Lenso as part of a major expansion of the text by [[Pablo Hidalgo]]. Lenso's newly created biography first identified the character as the aforementioned "Rogue Eleven" from the film [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''Star Wars'': Episode V ''The Empire Strikes Back'']].<ref name="GG3" /> The Rogue Eleven character was first mentioned in [[Donald F. Glut]]'s [[April]] [[1980]] [[Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back (novelization)|novelization]] of ''The Empire Strikes Back''.<ref name="ESB novel" />

Lenso and Rogue Ten's involvement in responding to the Imperial probe droid outside of Echo Base just prior to the Battle of Hoth has been expanded on in several sources to include additional scenes not included in the original film. Specifically, the April 1980 ''[[The Empire Strikes Back Storybook]]'', published just prior to the film's May release, makes mention of a group of snowspeeders that delivers Han Solo and Chewbacca to the location of the probe droid.<ref name="ESB Storybook">''[[The Empire Strikes Back Storybook]]''</ref> The [[September]] 1980 [[Star Wars (1977)|''Marvel Star Wars'']] [[Star Wars comic books|comic]] adaptation of ''The Empire Strikes Back'', [[Star Wars (1977) 39|''Star Wars'' (1977) 39]], likewise includes a panel in which a snowspeeder patrol delivers Solo and Chewbacca to the probe.<ref name="Marvel">[[Star Wars (1977) 39|''Star Wars'' (1977) 39]]</ref> The substance of this scene, first detailed in ''The Empire Strikes Back Storybook'', was referenced in the [[2008]] release of ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]'', under the "Rogue Eleven" entry, confirming that Lenso and Datch, specifically, transported Solo and Chewbacca to the probe,<ref name="CSWE" /> thus making ''The Empire Strikes Back Storybook'' the first [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] appearance, albeit indirectly, of Lenso's character.<ref name="ESB Storybook" /> [[Brian Daley]]'s [[1983]] [[The Empire Strikes Back (radio)|radio adaption]] of ''The Empire Strikes Back'' and the radio drama's original script, published in [[1995]] in ''[[The Empire Strikes Back: The National Public Radio Dramatization]]'', also include unique dialogue for the scene, in which General Rieekan considers ordering Lenso and Rogue Ten to attack the probe themselves.<ref name="ESB radio drama" /><ref name="ESB script" /> In 2013, an [[Rogues Gallery (department)|article]] in [[Star Wars Insider 146|''Star Wars Insider'' 146]] linked Lenso's name to one of the unnamed pilots seen being briefed by Princess Leia during ''The Empire Strikes Back''.

Lenso is included among the Rogue Squadron starfighter unit in the [[2006]] [[Star Wars video games|PC game]] ''[[Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption]]''. However, it should be noted that Lenso and the Rogue Squadron unit only appear in "Galactic Conquest" and "Skirmish" modes, which are not considered part of the game's [[canon]]ical storyline.<ref name="FOC">''[[Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption]]''</ref>

Lenso's helmet, or a matching design was previously worn by [[John D. Branon/Legends|John D. Branon]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']] and [[Ace Merrick]] in the video game [[Star Wars: Rebel Assault II: The Hidden Empire|Rebel Assault II: ''The Hidden Empire'']].<ref name="MP Documentary">''[[The Making of "The Empire Strikes Back"]]''</ref>

